          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Who are Mizrahi Jews?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/yemeni-jewish-immigrants-israel-registration-operation-magic-carpet.png" alt="A group of Yemeni Jewish immigrants register with Israeli officials upon arriving in Israel during Operation Magic Carpet" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>A group of Yemeni Jewish immigrants register with Israeli officials upon arriving in Israel during Operation Magic Carpet. Credits: My Jewish Learning</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Mizrahi Jews, often mistaken for Sephardic Jews due to shared religious customs, have a distinct Middle Eastern heritage. The term <i>Mizrahi</i> means eastern in Hebrew, reflecting their roots in regions like modern-day Iraq (ancient Babylon), Iran (Persia), and Yemen. Both Sephardic and Mizrahi Jews survived many <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-04-2025-f1-9-pogroms-against-them" target="_blank" >pogroms against them</a> in the 1950s and 1960s. Mizrahi Jew communities date back to Late Antiquity (200s AD).</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Currently, most Mizrahi Jews reside in Israel or the US, often maintaining strong cultural ties to their ancestral homelands. Their culture has significantly influenced mainstream society in Israel, from Yemenite music and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-04-2025-f1-10-cuisine" target="_blank" >cuisine</a> to sacred arts.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Despite their contributions, social and political inequality persists as Ashkenazic Jews (European Jews) continue to dominate many leadership roles. They are also less likely to be favored for positions in Israeli society.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Contrary to popular belief, Israel's population is not “all European’ or even the majority. Currently, the Mizrahi and Sephardic Jews make up over half of Israel’s population, marking a shift in demographic and cultural influence.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
